Greetings to governor-general of Bahamas 
 &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, July 18 (KCNA) -- Kim Yong Nam, President of the presidium of the DPRK Supreme People's Assembly, sent a message of greetings to governor-general Orville Alton Turnquest of the Commonwealth of the Bahamas Monday on his 71st birthday. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   Extending congratulations to the governor-general on his birthday, Kim in the message wished him success in his work for the prosperity of the country as well as good health and happiness.

DPRK-Japan working-level contact held 
 &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  Pyongyang, July 18 (KCNA) -- A communique on the working-level contact held between the Democratic People's Republic of Korea and Japan was published today. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   According to the communique, the DPRK and Japan had unofficial negotiations as regards the bilateral relations and decided to publish the agreed results as follows: &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   1. Both sides decided to hold the talks between the foreign ministers of the DPRK and Japan on July 26 during the ASEAN regional forum to be held in Bangkok. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   2. Both sides decided to hold the 10th intergovernmental full-dress talks for opening diplomatic relations between the DPRK and Japan and talks between Red Cross organizations of the two countries at an early date and arrange the third hometown visit of Japanese women in the DPRK.

Remains of ancient Korea unearthed 
 &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, July 18 (KCNA) -- Remains and relics of ancient Korea were recently unearthed in the DPRK. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   The archaeology institute of the Academy of Social Sciences discovered 3 home-sites and 3 dolmens of ancient Korea from Phyodae remains in Honam-ri, Samsok district, Pyongyang. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   The newly unearthed relics include gourd-shape pot, human bones, pieces of pottery, star-shape axe and bamboo beads. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   A rectangular home-site covers 30-35 square metres. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   The stone cover of dolmen no. 1 is the biggest, 412 cm long and 348 cm wide. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   There are 20 holes 4-7 cm in diameter and 2 cm in depth on the upper side of the stone cover that look like a turtle back. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   All the holes are delicate and orderly in their making. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
Experts presume that they were used by people at that time for study of astrology or marking constellations. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   Two stone and earthen tombs and other relics belonging to the kingdom of Koguryo were also discovered.

U.S. move to go ahead with "NMD" system 
 &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, July 18 (KCNA) -- Rodong Sinmun today in a signed commentary assails the United States for intending to continue the anti-ballistic missile test for establishing the "National Missile Defense" system (NMD) despite its recent failure in its third test. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   The commentary says: &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   The United States claims that its "NMD" is for protecting its "security" from a "threat" from the DPRK. This, however, is a sheer lie. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   The United States is the world's biggest possessor of missiles and nuclear power. The U.S. move to establish the "NMD" is prompted by its aim to have military supremacy over the world. Its main target is big powers around the Korean peninsula. But, the "ABM treaty" is a stumbling block in carrying out its "NMD" plan. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   That is why the U.S. seeks to modify the "ABM treaty" under the pretext of a "missile threat" from the DPRK and establish an unlimited "missile defense" system at any cost. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 
By doing so it wants to contain those big powers around the Korean peninsula which are challenging its move to build "unipolar world" and keep Europe under its military control. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   With nothing can the United States conceal its sinister design and danger of the "NMD".

Kim Jong Il praised 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  Pyongyang, July 18 (KCNA) -- Rodong Sinmun today carries an article "Kim Jong Il, symbol of independence and dignity" written by Takashi Nada, chairman of the Society for the Study of the Juche Idea in Shikoku, Japan. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   The article has sub-titles "great champion," "politics and ability" and "great master of creation, incarnation of benevolence."&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   In the article Nada refers to facts about the victory the Korean people achieved by resolutely smashing the campaign launched by the imperialists over the suspected "North Korean nuclear development" in the early 1990s, and the west's pressure that followed it under the name of "special inspection." &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   It tells how General Secretary Kim Jong Il defied the imperialists' persistent "sanctions" and pulled through unprecedented ordeals and difficulties confronting the Korean people in the middle of the 1990s with his unique army-first politics. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   Kim Jong Il's leadership is characterized by scientific strategy and superbness, experienced leadership art and invariable constancy and determination, the article stresses, and continues: &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   The springboard from which the Korean people can build a powerful nation was provided in 4 years from the middle of the 1990s, the most difficult period in the history of socialist construction. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   Noting that he has studied the history of Kim Jong Il's independent politics for more than 20 years, Nada writes that witnessing realities in the DPRK, he was confident its people  would surely build a powerful nation early in the 21st century.

Oil-bearing flax bred 
 &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  Pyongyang, July 18 (KCNA) -- The Academy of Agricultural Science in the DPRK recently succeeded in breeding oil-bearing flax, a new species of industrial crops. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   This will open a prospect of solving the problem of oil in food industry and other sectors. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   Flax seed contains over 45 percent of oil or more than double time that of bean. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   Flax from which oil is extracted can be used as a raw material for food industry as it contains 32 percent of protein and other nutriments. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   Its stalks can also be used in producing good-quality paper. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   One ton of stalks is enough to produce 500 kg of paper. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
   Boiled oil, lac and printing ink can be made from flax.
